'''Kinegamori Kofun''' ({{ill|Kinegamori Kofun|ja|杵ガ森古墳|12=draft}}) is a {{ill|Keyhole-shaped Kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Aizubange|ja|会津坂下町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft}}. It is part of the {{ill|Unai Aotsu Kofun Group|ja|宇内青津古墳群|12=draft}} and is Historic Site1 as a Fukushima Prefecture Historic Site.

Kinegamori Kofun is recognized as one of the oldest kofun in the Tohoku region.

== Overview ==
Located west of the city center of Aizubange, along the western bank of the typeer Miyagawa River (Tsurunumagawa), this keyhole-shaped Kofun faces south. Surrounding it are other ancient Kofuns, including Usagamori Kofun and Maigamori Kofun (now disappeared), which illustrate the region's prosperity during the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}}<ref name="description_panel"/>.

The rear section of Kinegamori Kofun is a two-tiered construction, while the details of the front section are unclear due to erosion<ref name="description_panel"/>. Its distinctive paddle-shaped design resembles that of the earliest keyhole-shaped mound, {{ill|Hashihaka Kofun|ja|箸墓古墳|12=draft}}, in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft}}, though Kinegamori is about one-sixth the size of Hashihaka<ref name="description_panel"/>. The mound is encircled by a moat<ref name="description_panel"/>.

The mound was first noted in the historical text ''Shinpen Aizu Fudoki'' as a mound, but it was officially identified during an archaeological survey in 1961. Before excavations, only part of the rear section was visible, with the remainder buried under rice fields. Excavations during 1990 revealed that the mound, previously thought to be circular, was actually a keyhole-shaped kofun. Additional findings included a surrounding moat, pit dwellings, and 10 {{ill|Square Kofuns|ja|方形周溝墓|12=draft}}<ref name="description_panel"/>. burial goods such as {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft}} suggest the mound was constructed in the late 3rd to early 4th century, making it one of the oldest kofun in Tohoku.

== area ==
The area of the mound are as follows<ref name="description_panel"/>:
* Total length: 45.6 meters
* Rear section:
** Diameter: 25.6 meters
** Height: ~2 meters
* Front section:
** Length: 24 meters
** Width: 19 meters

== Inarizuka Site ==
[[File:Inarizuka-iseki (Aizubange).JPG|thumb|200px|right|Inarizuka Site]]
The '''Inarizuka Site''' ({{ill|Inarizuka Site|ja|稲荷塚遺跡|12=draft}}) is an early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}} site near Kinegamori Kofun.

Excavations from 1990 to 1991 uncovered 15 pit dwellings, 3 {{ill|pillar-supported buildings|ja|掘立柱建物|12=draft}}, and 10 square Kofuns<ref name="description_panel"/>. These findings suggest that the site initially functioned as a settlement during the early Kofun period. Kinegamori Kofun was later constructed on the site, with additional Kofuns built nearby for individuals associated with the kofun.

In 2017, an additional 13 square Kofuns were discovered, bringing the total to 23, making it the largest collection of square Kofuns in Fukushima Prefecture<ref>[http://www.minyu-net.com/news/news/FM2017dd22-222147.php "Fukushima Prefecture’s Largest 'Square Kofun Group' Discovered at Inarizuka Site"] (''Minyu'', November 22, 2017).</ref>.

== designation1 ==
=== Fukushima Prefecture Designated Historic Site ===
* Historic Site
** Kinegamori Kofun - Designated on March 22, 1996<ref name="aizubange">[http://www.town.aizubange.fukushima.jp/soshiki/30/285.html "List of Historic Site in Aizubange"] (Aizubange Town website).</ref>.

