The mound was first noted in the historical text ''Shinpen Aizu Fudoki'' as a mound, but it was officially identified during an archaeological survey in 1961. Before excavations, only part of the rear section was visible, with the remainder buried under rice fields. Excavations during 1990 revealed that the mound, previously thought to be circular, was actually a keyhole-shaped kofun. Additional findings included a surrounding moat, pit dwellings, and 10 {{ill|Square Kofuns|ja|方形周溝墓|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofuns|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 弥生時代の墓制|1=Funerary practices of the Yayoi period|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11487466}}<ref name="description_panel"/>. burial goods such as [[:en:Haji pottery|Haji pottery]] suggest the mound was constructed in the late 3rd to early 4th century, making it one of the oldest kofun in Tohoku.

== area ==
The area of the mound are as follows<ref name="description_panel"/>:
* Total length: 45.6 meters
* Rear section:
** Diameter: 25.6 meters
** Height: ~2 meters
* Front section:
** Length: 24 meters
** Width: 19 meters

== Inarizuka Site ==
[[File:Inarizuka-iseki (Aizubange).JPG|thumb|200px|right|Inarizuka Site]]
The '''Inarizuka Site''' ({{ill|Inarizuka Site|ja|稲荷塚遺跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inarizuka Site|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}) is an early [[:en:Kofun period|Kofun period]] site near Kinegamori Kofun.

Excavations from 1990 to 1991 uncovered 15 pit dwellings, 3 [[:en:Post in ground|pillar-supported buildings]], and 10 square Kofuns<ref name="description_panel"/>. These findings suggest that the site initially functioned as a settlement during the early Kofun period. Kinegamori Kofun was later constructed on the site, with additional Kofuns built nearby for individuals associated with the kofun.

In 2017, an additional 13 square Kofuns were discovered, bringing the total to 23, making it the largest collection of square Kofuns in Fukushima Prefecture<ref>[http://www.minyu-net.com/news/news/FM2017dd22-222147.php "Fukushima Prefecture’s Largest 'Square Kofun Group' Discovered at Inarizuka Site"] (''Minyu'', November 22, 2017).</ref>.

